<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Taking A Step Back<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.44)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10245'>Elliot "Ringbearer77" Ross</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10245&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> April 18, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> When building a deck, it is important to take a look at your creation from many different angles. Many times you may have a great combo or theme idea, but in a real game situation it does not work like you planned. This article will give you some help in putting together a solid deck that is fun to play. Whether you are building a deck from scratch or modifying an existing deck, these guidelines should prove useful. <br>
<br>
1.	Have a Clear Objective<br>
<br>
The first thing you should look at when deck building is what you want your deck to do. You may be just having fun with a theme deck, or trying to win tournaments. Either way, it is important to keep your deck objective in mind throughout the deck building process. If you are trying to win, know which win condition you are trying to achieve and do not stray from it. For example, if you are trying to race to site nine with your fellowship, then don&#8217;t try to set up your shadow side to corrupt your opponents&#8217; ringbearer. In this case you are just trying to keep them from moving further than you so that you can win first, not corrupt or kill them. If you lose the focus of your deck, it definitely will not play well. That is why you need to keep the objective of your deck in the forefront of your mind. <br>
<br>
2.	Defense<br>
<br>
It is important to know how your deck will defend against anything your opponent could play against you. Once again, here it is important to know your objective. You cannot defend against everything, so you need to decide what is important to defend against so that you can obtain your objective. Here is a good list of questions to ask when thinking about defense. <br>
<br>
·	How will my deck defend against the Moria Culture?<br>
·	How will my deck defend against the Ringwraiths?<br>
·	How will my deck defend against the Sauron Culture?<br>
·	How will my deck defend against the Uruk Hai?<br>
·	How would my deck defend against itself?<br>
·	How do I keep my fellowship alive?<br>
·	What are my friends/local players playing or not playing that I have to worry about?<br>
<br>
These are just a few questions to get you thinking about what to ask while building your deck. It is up to you to decide what questions are important to you.<br>
<br>
3.	Deck Speed <br>
<br>
Another thing that is important in building a deck is your deck speed. You need to find a good balance of speed between your fellowship and shadow side. Some cultures are faster than others. It is good to pair your deck with one slow and one fast. For instance, if your shadow side goes through cards quickly (like Moria Orcs) then you would be well off to play a slower fellowship side (like a Hobbit Healing Deck). If your cultures are too slow, you will not be able to draw the cards you need quick enough. If your cultures are too fast, you will run out of cards too soon. Having a balance allows you to have the cards that you need in your hand at the right time, without running out of cards too soon. <br>
<br>
Obviously there is more to deck building than what is laid out here, but this should give you some general things to think about before, during, and after you put together your masterpiece. <br>
